== Social media

$=>$ *Zuckerberg fired the fact-checkers. We tested their replacement* : _August 2025_ : When a hoax about Trump went viral, (I) went on social media to try to set the record straight. (I) drafted a note debunking images claiming to show Trump sleeping during the ceremony, with proofs. None of that mattered, the community note never got added to a post because not enough other uers voted it was 'helpful'. Over four months, (I)'ve drafted 65 notes debunking conspiracy theories, 3 of them got published. Zuckerberg fired professional fact-checkers, leaving users to fight falsehoods with community notes.

$=>$ *Australia's social media ban won't protect kids -- it'll put them more at risk* : _December 2024_ : Australia has recently made the decision to ban children under 16 from social media -- a policy which the government will enforce via untersed age verification (AV) technology. The move has reignited debates about balancing online safety with privacy and freedoms. Efforts to protect children must not rely on thousands of websites globally to implement controls that are far from perfect to begin with. It is absurd to sacrifice privacy, fundamental rights, and safety on the altar of an unachievable kit. Website-based AV also create new security risks. By requiring websites to store vast amounts of personal data, they become lucrative targets from hackers.

$=>$ *Everything the right -- and the left -- are getting wrong about the Online Safety Act* : _August 2025_ : Last week, the UK's Online Safety Act came into force. Disdain from the right isn't surprising. The companies will now have to assess the risk their platforms pose of disseminationg the kind of racist misinformation that fuelled last year's summer riots. What does the act actually do ? It requires online services to assess the risk of harm -- whether illegal content such as childs sexual abuse material, or, in the case of service accessed by children, content such as porn or suicide promotion -- and implement proportionate systems to reduce those risks. Rather than making decisiosn to remove content reactively, or in order to appease politican, tech companies will now need to demonstrate they have taken reasonable steps to prevent this content from appearing in the first place.

